## The fetch Promise and HTTP Error Handling

The Fetch API makes a deliberate distinction that trips up almost every developer the first time: a fetch that receives *any* HTTP response — 200, 201, 400, 404, 500 — resolves its Promise successfully. Only a failure at the network layer rejects it.

This design reflects what `fetch` actually does: it sends a request and retrieves a response. Retrieving a 404 response is a network success. Whether that response represents a business-logic error is for application code to decide.

### The res.ok shorthand
The `Response` object exposes two ways to inspect the status:
- `res.status` — the numeric HTTP status code (200, 404, 500, etc.)
- `res.ok` — a boolean that is `true` when the status is 200–299, `false` for everything else

The idiomatic guard is:
```js
.then(res => {
  if (!res.ok) throw new Error(res.statusText);
  return res.json();
})
```

Throwing inside a `.then()` handler immediately rejects the chain. All subsequent `.then()` callbacks are skipped and the first `.catch()` fires. This is the same mechanism as a Promise rejection — you are not doing anything special, just converting an HTTP error into a JavaScript exception that the existing error-handling path already knows how to handle.

### Why the SyntaxError happens
APIs return different bodies for errors. Some return JSON (`{"error": "not found"}`). Many — especially frameworks like Express, Next.js, or nginx default error pages — return HTML. When `res.json()` tries to parse an HTML document, the `<` of `<!DOCTYPE` is immediately invalid JSON and it throws `SyntaxError: Unexpected token '<'`. That SyntaxError propagates to `.catch()`, but it carries no useful information about the HTTP status — only that JSON parsing failed. Users see either a cryptic parser error or, in the worst case, a component crash if there is no `.catch()` at all.

### Reading the error body
For APIs that return structured error JSON even on error responses, you can parse the body *after* confirming the status:
```js
.then(async res => {
  if (!res.ok) {
    const body = await res.json().catch(() => ({ message: res.statusText }));
    throw new Error(body.message ?? res.statusText);
  }
  return res.json();
})
```
The nested `.catch(() => ...)` handles the case where the error body is HTML rather than JSON — it falls back to `res.statusText` so the outer catch always gets a string.

### A reusable wrapper
In any codebase that makes more than a few fetch calls, defining a thin wrapper pays off quickly:
```js
async function apiFetch(url, options) {
  const res = await fetch(url, options);
  if (!res.ok) throw new Error(`${res.status} ${res.statusText}`);
  return res.json();
}
```
All callers get automatic status checking without repeating the pattern, and the error always carries the HTTP status for logging and debugging.

### Common variations of this bug
- `fetch` in a `useEffect` or event handler with no `.catch()` or try/catch — unhandled promise rejection, silent in production, logged as an error in the console.
- Treating `.catch()` as a complete error handler while not checking `res.ok` — catches only network and parse errors, silently swallows all HTTP errors that return parseable JSON.
- Checking `res.status === 200` specifically and missing 201, 204, or other valid 2xx codes — use `res.ok` instead of a specific status check.
- Error bodies returned as JSON with a 200 status (an anti-pattern in some older APIs) — `res.ok` will be true; you have to inspect the body shape.
- `res.json()` called on a 204 No Content response — the body is empty, JSON parse throws on empty input.
